<quiz>
    <question>
        <prompt>The Equal Rights Amendment (ERA) faced opposition in the 1920s from:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Male politicians only</option>
            <option letter="b">Women's groups concerned about protective legislation</option>
            <option letter="c">Religious organizations</option>
            <option letter="d">Business associations</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>The ERA, proposed by Alice Paul in 1923, faced significant opposition from women's groups and labor organizations who feared it would eliminate protective legislation for working women. Groups like the Women's Trade Union League argued that the amendment's absolute equality would invalidate laws setting maximum hours and minimum wages for women workers, highlighting divisions within the women's movement over equality versus protection.</explanation>
    </question>
</quiz>
